        "full_text": "So, chapter three, processes, okay, so the process concept now, we should be familiar with the process concept. We have already defined the process and we have already said that the process is a program in execution and that a process is an active entity while the program is a passive entity. And if we have multiple instances of the same program or the same application running, then each of these instances will be a separate process. And from operating system point of view, they will all be, you know, each one of them will be a separate process. And the operating system will not even, will not even know that there are instances of the same application because they may be behaving differently. It's the same application but, you know, they may be doing different things. Okay, so what does the process look like in memory? In memory, this is the memory layout of a process. There is the text section which is the code. So this is the code segment. And there is data section. There is the key and there is the stack. Now we know what's in the text, the code. But now what's in the data, what's in the heap, what's in the stack? What kinds of variables are placed in the data section? What kind of variables are in the heap and what kind of variables are in the stack? Okay, so what do we have in the data? Code. Code. And static. Yeah, global and static. Yeah, that's correct. So in the data section, we have global and static variables. So what do we have on the stack? Local. Local, yeah, local. Local. Local, yeah. On the stack, we have local variables and? Function code. What's that? Function code. The parameters, not the code. So the code is here. I mean the function code. Yeah, function, yeah, the parameters for the function code. So we have this, you know, the stack frame has local variables, function parameters, return value, return address, the data that is needed to implement a function code, not the code, okay? Now what's on the heap? Dynamically allocated variables. Yeah, exactly. On the heap, we have dynamically allocated variables. Now, process states. Now the state of a process, so this is, these are extremely important concepts here. So when a process is first created and admitted to the system, the system is going to put it in the ready state, okay? So it's, when the process is first admitted, it's in the ready state, which means that it's ready to take the CPU. As soon as the operating system decides to give it the CPU. So it's like I'm ready. And, but other processes are ready. And there is a limited number of CPUs, possibly one CPU, or maybe two or four CPUs, but there are 10 or 20 processes in the system. So the scheduler will be selecting one process for each CPU. For each CPU, there will be one process that will be run on that CPU. And when a process is selected by the scheduler, the state of that process will change from ready to running, okay? So the process is running. When a process is running, different things can happen. One possible, one possible event is just normal termination. If a process just terminates, comes to its end and terminates, it will be in the terminated state, will just terminate. A process may request I.O. If a process requests I.O., then the system will put it in the waiting state. So it will be in the waiting state until? I.O. is returning? Yeah, until that I.O. completes, that I.O. request, until the device completes processing that I.O. request. Then the point here, the key point is, when the device completes the I.O. request, the system is not just going to give it the CPU. Okay? Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. It will put it in the ready state. You never go from waiting to running. You have to go through the ready state, so you will be waiting in line. You will be in that ready queue, and then the scheduler will pick one process per CPU, one process for each CPU to be in the running state. Now, when an interrupt happens, now I'm going to ask you, I'm going to ask the question, a process is running, and there is an interrupt that put the process in the ready state. What kind of interrupt was that? It's giving it like a time interrupt. Yeah, exactly. That's the time interrupt. So if it's a time interrupt, you know, the time quantum that the system gave to the process expired, then the time interrupt will get triggered, and that will put the process in the ready state. The system will put the process in the ready state. And the kernel will take over. Now, remember, the main point here to remember is that when a process is waiting and the IO completes, it's in the ready state. It doesn't go directly to the running state. Also, when a process is waiting for the CPU, when a process is waiting for the CPU, it's waiting for the CPU. We do not call it waiting. Its state is not waiting. Its state is ready. You know, so even though, you know, in English, we can say the process is waiting for the CPU, but the technical term that is used to describe the state of that process is ready. So when you say ready, it means it's in the ready queue, and it's waiting for the CPU. Okay? Any questions on these transitions? Because this is very important. Yes? So you'd say it's ready for the CPU? Yeah, it's ready for the CPU. So when an exception gets generated because the process is doing something that it isn't supposed to? Okay. How is that reflected here? Okay, that's a good question. So if an exception is generated, a process is running, of course, because it can run. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. Okay. No. It does not generate an exception if it's not running. Then what will, what kind of transition will take place? Which state will it transition? Ready. Ready? Oh, we're generating . Yeah, that means the system is going to terminate that process. So if a process performs an invalid operation, the system will terminate that process. So you can say exception will go, it will take the process to the terminated state. Yeah? Can you explain going from running to waiting again? So it says IO event. Yeah, so a process requests IO by making a system call. So when it makes a system call, the kernel takes over. And when the kernel takes over, it will send the request to the IO device, and it will mark the process as waiting. So it would send the state of the process to waiting. And the process will stay waiting until the IO device completes processing the request and notifies the operating system. How does the IO device notify the system that the process has completed? How does the IO device notify the system? The IO device is a hardware. It doesn't make system calls. It's a network. It's a network. Yeah. It generates a network. It's a network."
