            "title": "Process Memory Layout: Text, Data, Heap, and Stack Segments",
            "start_sec": 86.48,
            "summary": "The professor presents the in-memory layout of a process, identifying four segments: text (compiled code), data, heap, and stack. Through interactive Q&A with students, each segment's contents are pinpointed: the data section holds global and static variables, the stack holds local variables plus stack frame metadata (function parameters, return value, return address), and the heap holds dynamically allocated variables. The text segment is distinguished as the only region containing executable code. Understanding this layout is critical because the OS and compiler rely on these boundaries for memory management and protection.",
