            "summary": "The professor defines a CPU burst as a contiguous sequence of CPU-only operations \u2014 arithmetic, load, store \u2014 that contains no system calls or IO requests, while an IO burst begins the moment a system call (e.g., read from file or keyboard) is issued. He clarifies that even though a load or store may leave the CPU idle at the hardware level, the OS considers the process to be 'holding the CPU' during that time. The boundary between bursts is precisely the system call, after which the process transitions to a waiting state and must re-enter the ready queue before getting the CPU again. Understanding burst boundaries is essential because the entire scheduling model is built around this alternating CPU/IO burst structure.",
