            "summary": "The professor introduces the short-term (CPU) scheduler as the OS component that selects a process from the ready queue and assigns it the CPU, emphasizing that the 'ready queue' is a conceptual term and can be implemented as a FIFO queue, priority queue, or tree. He identifies the key scheduling decision points \u2014 when a process requests IO, is preempted by a timer interrupt, or terminates \u2014 and contrasts preemptive scheduling (where a hardware timer forcibly reclaims the CPU) with non-preemptive scheduling (where a process voluntarily releases the CPU). Preemptive scheduling requires a hardware timer and is the modern standard, while non-preemptive systems only reschedule when processes block or exit.",
