            "problem": "Three processes spend the following times in the ready queue during their lifetimes: P1 waits 4 ms, P2 waits 9 ms, and P3 waits 2 ms. Compute the average waiting time. Then explain why the lecture emphasizes average waiting time rather than only a single process's waiting time.",
            "hint": "Add the waiting times and divide by the number of processes.",
            "solution": "Step 1: Sum the waiting times: 4 + 9 + 2 = 15 ms.\nStep 2: Divide by the number of processes: 15 / 3 = 5 ms.\nSo the average waiting time is 5 ms.\nWhy average waiting time matters: Scheduling algorithms affect many processes, not just one. Average waiting time gives a single aggregate measure of how the system performs over a workload. The lecture notes that this chapter mainly compares algorithms using average waiting time because it is a standard optimization target, though other goals such as minimizing maximum response time may matter in interactive systems.",
            "bloom_level": "application",
