            "problem": "A designer shortens the time quantum dramatically in a preemptive time-sharing system. Predict two likely benefits and two likely costs using the lecture's performance criteria.",
            "hint": "Think about user responsiveness versus overhead and resource efficiency.",
            "solution": "Likely benefits:\n1. Better response time: Interactive users may see faster initial responses because the CPU rotates among processes more frequently.\n2. Better perceived fairness: No process holds the CPU for long before others get a chance.\nLikely costs:\n1. Increased dispatch overhead: More frequent timer interrupts and context switches mean more dispatch latency is paid.\n2. Lower effective CPU utilization / throughput: If too much time is spent switching rather than executing useful work, system efficiency falls.\nConclusion: A shorter time quantum may improve interactivity but hurt resource utilization, showing the tradeoff emphasized in the lecture.",
