            "summary": "The professor opens with a recap of the previous memory management chapter before introducing virtual memory. Contiguous memory allocation is reviewed as the baseline approach, with fragmentation identified as its critical flaw \u2014 the system cannot use free memory that is not a single contiguous block. Segmentation and paging are presented as non-contiguous alternatives that divide a process's address space into manageable pieces, giving the memory manager far more flexibility. The logical-vs-physical address space distinction is reviewed: pages appear as a contiguous block to the process but can be scattered across physical memory frames. This review establishes the conceptual groundwork on which virtual memory builds.",
