            "title": "Virtual Memory: Core Concept and Demand Paging",
            "start_sec": 217.03,
            "summary": "The professor introduces virtual memory's key insight: a running program uses only a small subset of its pages at any moment, so there is no need to load the entire address space into physical memory. A relatable analogy is used \u2014 running PowerPoint while only actively using the slide-display feature, leaving hundreds of other features' code pages completely unused and unnecessary to load. From this motivation, demand paging is defined as fetching pages from disk only when they are actually referenced. Pure demand paging (strictly on-demand, no page loaded until referenced) is contrasted with practical demand paging, where the OS may prefetch a few adjacent pages by exploiting locality of reference. This chapter establishes the central mechanism that makes virtual memory feasible.",
