            "title": "Advantages of Virtual Memory: Increased Concurrency and Reduced Disk I/O",
            "start_sec": 565.59,
            "summary": "The professor enumerates two major practical benefits of virtual memory using a concrete numeric example: a 1000-page program that only needs 5 resident frames at a time. Because physical memory requirements per process shrink dramatically, far more processes can be loaded concurrently, giving the CPU scheduler more candidates and improving overall CPU utilization. The second benefit is reduced disk I/O \u2014 without virtual memory, loading a 1000-page program requires 1000 disk reads at startup; with demand paging, only the handful of needed pages are fetched, making process creation and context switching significantly faster. A summary slide consolidates the benefits: further separation between logical and physical memory, more programs running concurrently, more efficient process creation, and less disk access. This section justifies virtual memory as a practical performance win rather than just an abstraction.",
