            "summary": "The professor formally equates logical address space with virtual address space, explaining that the page table (part of the MMU) continues to serve as the mapping mechanism from virtual to physical addresses, but now must also track which pages are on disk. A detailed diagram is walked through showing an eight-page process: all pages reside on disk, but only pages 0, 2, and 5 are currently loaded into physical frames 4, 6, and 9 respectively, with valid bits (V) marking them as resident. The valid-invalid (V/I) bit is introduced as the key addition to each page table entry \u2014 V means the page is in physical memory; I means it is on disk and must be fetched before use. The process address space layout (code, data, heap, stack with a sparse hole in between) illustrates how virtual memory allows dynamic growth by allocating physical frames only on demand. This chapter bridges the conceptual model of virtual memory to its concrete hardware data structure.",
