            "summary": "A page fault is defined as the hardware exception raised when a process accesses a page whose valid-invalid bit is set to I, transferring control to the OS to fetch the missing page from disk into a free physical frame and update the page table entry. The professor highlights that page fault handling is inherently slow because disk access is orders of magnitude slower than memory, yet the OS mitigates this by context-switching to another ready process while waiting for the disk I/O to complete. The professor then poses the key question: if page faults are so expensive, why does virtual memory not cripple performance? The answer is locality of reference \u2014 programs tend to make many repeated accesses to a small working set of pages over a given time interval, so once a page is loaded it will be reused many times before a new fault is needed. Locality is thus the fundamental reason virtual memory is practical and not just theoretically appealing.",
