            "summary": "The professor pivots to the 0-1 Knapsack Problem\u2014a problem that greedy algorithms cannot solve\u2014and shows how dynamic programming applies. A concrete example (three items with weights 2, 3, 5 kg and values $3, $4, $6; capacity C=8) is introduced and used throughout. The DP formulation is built from trivial base cases (zero items or zero capacity yield value 0), then the problem is grown in two dimensions: number of items considered (rows) and knapsack capacity (columns). The key recurrence is derived: for each item X with capacity J, either take X (gaining value(X) plus the best fit in remaining capacity J\u2212w(X) using prior items, read from the previous row) or skip X (copying the previous row's value at column J), and take the maximum.",
