            "summary": "The professor analyzes the running time (Theta(nC) for table-filling, Theta(n) for traceback) and addresses a subtle but critical point: although the algorithm appears polynomial, it is technically exponential in the true input size. The value C is encoded in only log(C) characters, so the loop running C times represents an exponential blow-up relative to the size of C's representation\u2014making this a pseudo-polynomial algorithm. Correctness is argued via an implicit inductive proof: the base cases are trivially correct, and the recurrence ensures that if all smaller subproblem entries are correct, each new entry is correct, mirroring a formal induction step. The lecture closes by connecting this to NP-completeness: because 0-1 Knapsack has a pseudo-polynomial algorithm, it is classified as weakly NP-complete rather than strongly NP-complete.",
