            "solution": "The dynamic programming algorithm runs in Theta(nC), so here the table-filling time is proportional to 100 x 10,000 = 1,000,000 operations up to constants. This is polynomial in the numeric value of C.\n\nHowever, formal complexity theory measures running time against the input size in bits. The number 10,000 does not require 10,000 symbols to write in binary; it requires only about log2(10,000), which is around 14 bits. So an algorithm whose running time depends linearly on C may actually be exponential in the bit-length of C.\n\nTherefore Theta(nC) is not polynomial in input length in the standard sense. It is polynomial in the numerical value of the capacity, which is why it is called pseudo-polynomial.\n\nThis is exactly why 0-1 knapsack can have this DP algorithm and still be NP-complete: the problem is weakly NP-complete, not strongly NP-complete.",
