        "teach_back_prompt": "Explain to a classmate who missed class why the naive recursive Fibonacci algorithm blows up so quickly, and then show how that same idea of reusing subproblems leads to a dynamic programming solution for 0-1 knapsack that is pseudo-polynomial rather than truly polynomial in the input length.",
        "common_traps": [
          {
            "trap": "Thinking Fibonacci recursion is only slow because n is large, not because the same subproblems are recomputed many times.",
            "consequence": "You miss the real reason dynamic programming helps and fail to recognize overlapping subproblems in other problems.",
            "fix": "Track repeated calls like F(n-2) appearing in multiple branches; the issue is duplicate work, not just deep recursion."
          },
          {
            "trap": "Confusing polynomial time in the value of a number with polynomial time in the length of its encoding.",
            "consequence": "You may incorrectly label pseudo-polynomial algorithms as truly polynomial and misunderstand complexity class claims.",
            "fix": "Always ask: is the running time measured against the number of bits/characters of the input, or against the numeric magnitude itself?"
          },
          {
            "trap": "Assuming every NP-complete problem with a dynamic programming solution is actually polynomial-time solvable.",
            "consequence": "You may think knapsack being solvable by DP contradicts NP-completeness.",
            "fix": "Remember that pseudo-polynomial time depends on numeric capacity values; it can still be exponential in the input length."
          },
          {
            "trap": "Treating the 0-1 knapsack problem as if fractional selection were allowed.",
            "consequence": "You solve a different problem with a greedy strategy and get the wrong answer for the lecture\u2019s actual problem.",
            "fix": "Keep the '0-1' restriction in mind: each item is either taken once or not taken at all."
          }
        ]
