            "title": "Graph Representations Review and BFS/DFS Overview",
            "start_sec": 7.5,
            "summary": "The professor recaps the previous lecture on adjacency list vs. adjacency matrix representations, then establishes the adjacency list as the default for all graph algorithms because traversing neighbor lists is the core operation in both BFS and DFS. He introduces BFS and DFS as today's two main topics, emphasizing a deeper understanding beyond surface familiarity since they form the foundation for more advanced graph algorithms. A visual graph example is used to contrast breadth-first traversal \u2014 which visits nodes level by level outward from the source \u2014 with depth-first traversal, which dives along a single path before backtracking. This conceptual distinction motivates everything that follows in the lecture.",
