            "hint": "Only the tie among same-level discoveries may change. Distances depend on levels, not on the exact parent chosen among valid shortest predecessors.",
            "solution": "With A: [D, B], start BFS from A.\n\n1. Dequeue A. Discover D first, then B.\n- D.d = 1, parent[D] = A\n- B.d = 1, parent[B] = A\nQueue = [D, B]\n\n2. Dequeue D. Neighbors: A, E, H.\n- E.d = 2, parent[E] = D\n- H.d = 2, parent[H] = D\nQueue = [B, E, H]\n\n3. Dequeue B. Neighbors: A, C, E.\n- C.d = 2, parent[C] = B\n- E already discovered from D, so parent[E] stays D\nQueue = [E, H, C]\n\n4. Continue:\n- E may discover F => F.d = 3, parent[F] = E\n- H may discover G => G.d = 3, parent[G] = H\n\nCompared with the previous BFS, parent[E] changes from B to D because D is processed before B in this traversal order. Depending on later order, parent[F] may also change if F is first discovered from E instead of C.\n\nDistances do not change:\n- A: 0\n- B, D: 1\n- C, E, H: 2\n- F, G: 3\n\nReason: BFS still processes vertices level by level. Changing adjacency-list order can change which shortest path is chosen, but not the shortest-path length itself.",
