            "solution": "A correct O(V + E) analysis has three parts.\n\n1. Initialization:\nThe algorithm sets distance (and often parent) for every vertex once.\nThis costs O(V).\n\n2. Queue operations:\nEach vertex is discovered at most once, so each vertex is enqueued at most once and dequeued at most once.\nThus all queue operations together cost O(V).\n\n3. Scanning adjacency lists:\nWhen a vertex u is dequeued, BFS scans every entry in Adj[u]. Over the entire execution, the total number of adjacency-list entries scanned is the sum of the lengths of all adjacency lists.\n- For a directed graph, this total is O(E).\n- For an undirected graph, each edge appears twice, once in each endpoint's list, which is still O(E).\n\nTherefore total time is:\nO(V) + O(V) + O(E) = O(V + E).\n\nWhy it is not O(VE):\nThat would incorrectly assume that for each vertex, BFS scans all edges in the graph. It does not. It scans only that vertex's own adjacency list, and these scans add up to E across the full algorithm.",
