            "summary": "The professor opens by reviewing the progression from DFAs/NFAs (regular languages) and PDAs (context-free languages) to motivate the need for a more powerful model. The Turing Machine is introduced as that model \u2014 capable of simulating any general-purpose computer and serving as the formal mathematical definition of an algorithm. The professor explains that an algorithm is a well-defined sequence of steps for solving a problem, and that a TM captures exactly this notion. Crucially, the lecture previews a fundamental limitation: not all problems are solvable by algorithms, meaning some problems lie beyond any computer's reach.",
