            "title": "Turing Machine Architecture: Infinite Tape, Read/Write Head, and Tape Alphabet",
            "start_sec": 230.23,
            "summary": "The professor gives a concrete structural description of a TM, contrasting it with the stack memory of a PDA. The TM's key architectural feature is an infinite (unbounded) tape that serves as both input storage and general working memory, with a blank symbol marking the end of the input. A read/write head is positioned at the first symbol of the input and can scan the tape. The professor introduces the distinction between the input alphabet \u03a3 (symbols in the string) and the tape alphabet \u0393 (a strict superset of \u03a3 that also includes special symbols like the blank), explaining why the blank cannot belong to \u03a3.",
