            "summary": "The professor draws the complete nested hierarchy of language classes, arguing that every decidable language is recognizable (but not vice versa) because a TM that always halts trivially satisfies the weaker recognizability condition. The hierarchy from smallest to largest is: Regular \u2282 Context-Free \u2282 Turing-Decidable \u2282 Turing-Recognizable, with the argument that a more powerful machine can always simulate a less powerful one using a subset of its features. The professor also introduces the classical alternative names used in the literature: Turing-decidable languages are called recursive languages, and Turing-recognizable languages are called recursively enumerable (RE) languages.",
