            "start_sec": 2214.63,
            "summary": "The professor formalizes the TM's transition function \u03b4: Q \u00d7 \u0393 \u2192 Q \u00d7 \u0393 \u00d7 {L, R}, showing with a concrete example how a single transition reads a symbol, writes a replacement symbol, changes state, and moves the head left or right. The full formal definition of a TM as a 7-tuple (Q, \u03a3, \u0393, \u03b4, q_start, q_accept, q_reject) is then presented, paralleling the 5-tuple for DFAs and 6-tuple for PDAs. The professor explains why an explicit reject state is necessary \u2014 unlike FAs where termination is implicit when input is exhausted, a TM may re-scan the tape multiple times, so a designated reject state is the only reliable termination signal. Finally, the professor argues that requiring a single accept state does not reduce generality, by analogy with the NFA-to-single-accept-state construction.",
