            "solution": "If a language L is Turing-decidable, then there exists a TM M that halts on every input, accepting strings in L and rejecting strings not in L. That same machine M also satisfies the definition of recognition, because it certainly accepts all strings in L. Therefore every decidable language is recognizable.\n\nThe converse fails because recognizability is weaker. A recognizer for L only needs to accept members of L. For nonmembers, it may reject or loop forever. A decider is not allowed to loop forever on any input. So there can be recognizable languages for which no machine halts on all inputs while deciding membership. Therefore not every recognizable language is decidable.",
