            "title": "Regular Expression Examples: Even-Length and Odd-Length String Languages",
            "start_sec": 2722.61,
            "summary": "To build regex fluency before using flex, the professor works through two closed-form regular expression examples. For strings of even length over \u03a3={0,1}, the regex is (\u03a3\u03a3)* \u2014 pairing symbols and starring the pair \u2014 with the edge case that the empty string (length 0) is considered even. For strings of odd length, the regex is \u03a3(\u03a3\u03a3)*, placing one mandatory symbol before the even-length suffix (or equivalently after it). These examples reinforce how to reason about string structure algebraically using concatenation, union, and Kleene star.",
